 When is Miss Howe getting back 
     with my real clothes?      

08:59.200 --> 09:01.900
     I can't go out like this.  

09:02.000 --> 09:04.000
        I mean, I know it was   
          the '70s and all,     

09:04.100 --> 09:06.700
 but who would dress in anything
        this dumb-looking?      

09:08.700 --> 09:11.900
    Those duds look familiar.   

09:13.700 --> 09:17.000
        "Property               
         of C. Clavin."         

09:17.800 --> 09:21.300
Deep inside, didn't             
we all know that?               

09:21.400 --> 09:22.900
        (laughing)              

09:23.000 --> 09:24.700
                  These are your
            clothes, Mr. Clavin?

09:24.700 --> 09:26.000
         Yeah, I guess.         

09:26.100 --> 09:27.400
    Well, how'd they end up     
     in the lost and found?     

09:27.500 --> 09:28.800
 How did they end up in there?  

09:28.900 --> 09:31.000
Well, it was the '70s,          

09:31.000 --> 09:33.100
(chuckles):                     
and I was a swinger.            

09:35.500 --> 09:36.800
             Uh-oh.             

09:36.900 --> 09:38.700
I had some good times           
in those rags, Woody.           

09:38.700 --> 09:40.500
         Cliff, we don't want to
          hear about it, please.

09:40.600 --> 09:42.300
Huh? Oh, it was great.          

09:42.400 --> 09:43.700
You know, hey,                  
the disco scene,                

09:43.800 --> 09:44.700
                    grooving.   

09:44.800 --> 09:46.200
Ixnay, Cliff.                   

09:46.300 --> 09:47.600
          Yeah, it was          
      a great decade, huh?      

09:47.700 --> 09:48.900
    Hot-tubbing every night.    

09:48.900 --> 09:50.000
         I got rolfed.          

09:50.100 --> 09:51.200
WOODY:                          
Oh.                             

09:51.300 --> 09:53.600
    Please stop, Mr. Clavin.    

09:53.700 --> 09:56.000
    Oh, now I remember          
how I lost those clothes.       

09:56.000 --> 09:57.700
    Oh, don't say it;           
         don't say it.          

09:57.800 --> 09:59.300
I was streaking!                

09:59.400 --> 10:00.600
Oh! I knew it!                  

10:00.600 --> 10:02.600
I knew he was gonna             
say it!                         

10:02.700 --> 10:04.600
Of course, I was about          
three pounds lighter then.      

10:06.600 --> 10:07.900
                        FRASIER:
                        Woody...

10:08.000 --> 10:09.100
    I think it was              
a great sacrifice               

10:09.200 --> 10:10.700
     for you to give            
your clothes to Rebecca.        

10:10.800 --> 10:12.000
              It puts me in mind

10:12.100 --> 10:14.300
      of another novel by       
  my favorite British author.   

10:14.400 --> 10:16.200
      You know who I mean.      

10:16.300 --> 10:17.500
I'll give you a hint.           

10:17.500 --> 10:19.400
          Charles...?           

10:19.500 --> 10:21.700
                     In Charge? 

10:21.800 --> 10:23.700
    (laughs)                    

10:23.800 --> 10:25.700
Are you people really           
this ignorant                   

10:25.800 --> 10:27.700
or do you just do this          
to torture me?                  

10:27.700 --> 10:30.700
        Uh, sometimes the two   
                go hand-in-hand.

10:30.700 --> 10:32.000
All right.                      

10:32.100 --> 10:33.500
  Gather around,                
  everyone.                     

10:33.600 --> 10:35.700
I am going to right             
a horrible wrong.               

10:35.700 --> 10:38.000
I am going to read to you       
Dickens' classic,               

10:38.100 --> 10:39.600
 <i>A Tale of Two Cities,</i>          

10:39.700 --> 10:41.400
                and you will see
            just how much fun   

10:41.400 --> 10:42.900
        great literature can be.

10:42.900 --> 10:44.400
         (all groaning)         

10:44.400 --> 10:45.900
                        FRASIER:
                "Book the First.

